    <h1>Eleanor Tramountanas<br><span>Waymo Strategy Analysis</span></h1>
    <p class="header-intro">A case study in applied AI decision-making. Over seven steps, I worked through Waymo's core strategy challenges as a simulated strategy analyst — from training perception models to recommending the company's next city launch. Each step combined hands-on simulators with real business deliverables drafted in partnership with Claude.</p>
  </div>
</header>

<!-- SITUATION -->
<div class="situation">
  <div class="situation-inner">
    <div class="situation-label">The Situation</div>
    <p>Two weeks ago in Austin, Texas, a Waymo car hesitated for 14 seconds at an unprotected left turn. No safety issue — but the rider gave it a 2-star review and tweeted about it. Engineering flagged it as both a perception problem and a planner problem. The VP of Strategy asked me to figure out what that meant, and to recommend which city Waymo should launch in next.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<main>

  <!-- STEP 1 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 1</div>
    <h2>Deep Learning Basics</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>I started by training a small neural network from scratch — labeling images as "cat" or "not cat" and watching the model's feature weights shift with each example. What struck me was how mechanical the process felt: the network wasn't learning to understand cats, it was learning which pixel patterns reliably correlated with the label I gave it. A four-stage CNN visualization made this concrete, showing how raw pixels become edges, edges become shapes, and shapes become a classified object like "pedestrian, 94% confident."</p>
      <p>The most important concept from this step was the long-tail problem. A handful of common scenarios — stopped cars at a red light, a pedestrian in a crosswalk — make up the majority of real-world driving. But there are thousands of rare scenarios (a child in a Halloween costume, a mattress on the highway, first snow in a city that rarely sees it) that collectively matter enormously. A model trained only on common cases will fail exactly when the stakes are highest. This single insight explains every major data strategy decision in the rest of the lab.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- STEP 2 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 2</div>
    <h2>Deep Learning at Waymo</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>I evaluated three training-dataset vendors for Waymo's perception model — ranging from $100M of sunny Phoenix footage to $300M of edge-case-heavy rare scenarios. I trained a simulated network on each and compared how accuracy diverged between routine scenes and edge cases. The gap was stark: the cheapest dataset looked fine on overall accuracy but collapsed on the scenarios that actually cause incidents.</p>
      <p>I recommended Dataset B — the balanced option at $180M — and drafted the following CFO-facing email defending that choice on business terms rather than technical ones.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="artifact">
      <div class="artifact-label">Artifact · CFO Email</div>
      <p><strong>Subject:</strong> Training Data Vendor Recommendation: Dataset B</p>
      <p>Hi [CFO Name],</p>
      <p>I'm recommending we go with Dataset B (Balanced, $180M).</p>
      <p>Three reasons:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Safety baseline.</strong> Dataset A's Phoenix-only coverage leaves us underexposed to weather and edge conditions — a liability risk we can't accept at scale.</li>
        <li><strong>Regulatory positioning.</strong> Balanced condition coverage gives us a defensible safety record across the jurisdiction types we're targeting for expansion. Gaps in training data are increasingly a regulatory flashpoint.</li>
        <li><strong>Competitive headroom.</strong> At $80M less than Dataset C, we preserve capital to fund ongoing model improvements from real-world deployment data — keeping us competitive without betting everything on pre-launch perfection.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The tradeoff I'm accepting: Dataset B's 83% accuracy means we'll carry more residual risk than Dataset C would provide at launch. I'm confident our active learning pipeline closes that gap over time.</p>
      <p>Happy to walk through the analysis. Let me know.</p>
      <p>Eleanor Tramountanas</p>
    </div>
    <p class="drafted-note">Drafted with Claude and edited for voice and accuracy.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- STEP 3 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 3</div>
    <h2>World Models</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>Step 3 answered the question the long-tail problem raised: if rare scenarios barely appear in real-world data, how does Waymo train for them? The answer is world models — AI systems that have learned how reality works (how rain falls, how fog obscures, how drivers behave at dusk) and can compose entirely new scenarios from those ingredients without needing recorded footage of the specific event.</p>
      <p>I built scenarios using four ingredients — weather, time of day, road actors, and a wildcard — and calculated how many real-world miles each combination would require to encounter naturally. My most complex scenario (dense fog + dusk + a loose dog + active construction zone) would require roughly 150 million miles to appear in fleet data. The world model generated it in seconds. I then drafted the following internal brief making the business case for simulation investment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="artifact">
      <div class="artifact-label">Artifact · World Model Investment Brief</div>
      <p><strong>TO:</strong> [VP Name]<br>
      <strong>FROM:</strong> Eleanor Tramountanas<br>
      <strong>RE:</strong> World Model Simulation — Strategic Moat, Not R&D Overhead</p>
      <p>Fleet driving scales linearly. Rare events do not appear more often just because you drive more miles — they appear when conditions compound. Our world model breaks that constraint by composing known ingredients into novel scenarios on demand, without requiring those scenarios to have occurred in the real world first.</p>
      <p>Example: dense fog + dusk lighting + a loose dog + an active construction zone. Encountering this exact combination naturally would require roughly 150 million miles of fleet driving. We generated it in seconds using a world model. Waymo's model — built on Genie 3 transfer learning — didn't need prior footage of this scenario. It understood each element separately and combined them.</p>
      <p>Tesla's volume advantage is real, but it's only a solution to common-case coverage, not tail-risk coverage. The scenarios that cause fatalities are precisely the ones fleets rarely see. Simulating the long tail is not something more miles fixes.</p>
      <p>If we deprioritize simulation investment, we cede the ability to train proactively on catastrophic-but-rare events. We become reactive — waiting for the real world to surface scenarios that we could have already solved.</p>
      <p>The moat is not the simulator. It's the compounding library of edge cases competitors haven't encountered yet.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="drafted-note">Drafted with Claude and edited for voice and accuracy.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- STEP 4 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 4</div>
    <h2>Planning with Reinforcement Learning</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>This step introduced the prediction-decision gap: perception tells the car what's there, but the planner has to decide what to do about it. I used reinforcement learning to design a reward function for handling unprotected left turns — the specific maneuver that caused the Austin hesitation. The simulator gave me a 20-point penalty budget split across collisions, close calls, and wait time, and I had to hit three defensibility bars simultaneously: ≥95% completion rate, ≤1 collision, and average wait under 8 seconds.</p>
      <p>What the exercise made visceral was the alignment problem: the car optimizes exactly what you tell it to, no more. Weight collisions too heavily and it freezes. Weight wait time too heavily and it takes gaps that are too small. The defensible zone is narrow — and it requires explicitly accepting one tradeoff to hold the other two.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="artifact">
      <div class="artifact-label">Artifact · Safety Board Defense</div>
      <p>The reward function was evaluated against three safety bars on a 300-attempt left-turn test set. On completion rate, the policy achieved 294 successful turns (98%), clearing the ≥285 threshold. On collision avoidance, the policy recorded zero collisions, well within the ≤1 limit. On decisiveness, average wait time came in at 5 seconds, below the &lt;8-second ceiling.</p>
      <p>The penalty structure — collision at 7 points, close call at 7 points, and 6 points per second of excess waiting — was calibrated to weight physical safety outcomes more heavily than throughput. The explicit tradeoff accepted was modest hesitation: by penalizing wait time less severely than collision risk, the policy is biased toward caution at ambiguous gaps rather than assertive entry. This means passengers and other road users should expect slightly longer left-turn delays than an aggressive policy would produce. That delay is intentional — it is the mechanism by which the collision budget is preserved.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="drafted-note">Drafted with Claude and edited for voice and accuracy.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- STEP 5 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 5</div>
    <h2>Data Strategy &amp; the AI Business</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>Step 5 shifted from engineering to strategy. I studied the core contrast between Waymo's simulation-first approach and Tesla's fleet-first approach, then allocated a $1B data budget across five categories. The key insight was that not all spending creates a moat: sensor hardware and third-party data partnerships can be replicated by any rival with capital. The simulation library — specifically the accumulated judgment about which edge cases to prioritize and how to generate them — cannot be bought quickly.</p>
      <p>My final allocation: Fleet Expansion 30% / Simulation Capacity 35% / Human Labelers 15% / Sensor Upgrades 15% / Data Partnerships 5%. To test whether I'd internalized the three data-moat questions, I applied them to Spotify.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="artifact">
      <div class="artifact-label">Artifact · Data Moat Evaluation: Spotify</div>
      <h3>1. Where does their data come from?</h3>
      <p>Spotify's data comes from three interlocking sources: streaming behavior from 600M+ users (every play, skip, pause, playlist add, and repeat), creator-side data from the 10M+ artists and podcasters on the platform, and contextual signals like time of day, device type, and listener mood inferred from behavior patterns. The most strategically valuable layer isn't the audio files themselves — those are licensed, not owned — it's the behavioral graph: who listened to what, in what sequence, at what moment, and what they did next. No competitor can see that graph because it only exists inside Spotify's walls. Apple Music has subscribers; it doesn't have 17 years of granular skip data across every demographic on earth.</p>
      <h3>2. Does the pipeline keep getting better on its own?</h3>
      <p>Yes — and it compounds in both directions. Every new listener generates more behavioral signal, which improves recommendation quality, which retains listeners longer, which generates more signal. The Discover Weekly and Daily Mix algorithms get measurably better as the user base grows, not because engineers rewrote them, but because the training data deepened. The podcast side adds a second compounding loop: Spotify's exclusive podcast catalog drives listeners onto the platform, those listeners generate behavioral data, and that data improves ad targeting, which funds more exclusive content. The one-shot parts are the licensed music catalog and the hardware Spotify briefly tried (the Car Thing) — those don't compound. The behavioral graph does.</p>
      <h3>3. Can a competitor replicate it with money alone?</h3>
      <p>Partly. A well-funded rival — say, Apple or Amazon — can license the same music catalog, hire the same ML engineers, and build a comparable recommendation interface. What they cannot buy is 17 years of skip patterns, playlist behavior, and listening context across 600M users spanning every market from Lagos to São Paulo. That historical depth is what makes Spotify's "taste graph" accurate for cold-start users: Spotify can already make a good guess about what a 22-year-old in Nairobi likes based on cohort patterns no competitor has. Amazon Music could spend $5B tomorrow and still not have that. The gap is time, not money.</p>
      <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Spotify's data moat is strong — the behavioral graph compounds automatically with scale, is impossible to replicate on a short timeline, and creates a self-reinforcing loop that improves the core product without additional engineering investment.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="drafted-note">Drafted with Claude and edited for voice and accuracy.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- STEP 6 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step-number">Step 6</div>
    <h2>The Recommendation</h2>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>The final step required synthesizing everything. I analyzed three real social-license incidents — protest coning in San Francisco, a Waymo blocking a fire truck in Austin, taxi-union opposition in Miami — and chose response strategies for each. Then I evaluated four candidate cities against the full picture: perception readiness, world model needs, planner behavior, data-moat growth, and social license dynamics.</p>
      <p>I recommended Seattle. It offered tech-friendly regulators, no prior Waymo incident history to manage, and a driving environment that would meaningfully expand Waymo's weather edge-case library. The social license risks are real but navigable — unlike Atlanta's active NHTSA investigation or New York's legislative blockade.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="artifact">
      <div class="artifact-label">Artifact · Recommendation Memo to VP of Strategy</div>
      <div class="artifact-memo-header">
        <p><strong>TO:</strong> VP of Strategy, Waymo</p>
        <p><strong>FROM:</strong> Eleanor Tramountanas, Strategy Analyst</p>
        <p><strong>RE:</strong> City #5 Launch Recommendation</p>
        <p><strong>DATE:</strong> April 29, 2026</p>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Recommendation: Launch in Seattle.</strong> The combination of tech-friendly regulators, an untapped market with no prior Waymo history to overcome, and a driving environment that will meaningfully expand our edge-case data library makes Seattle the most defensible choice for City #5 right now.</p>
      <h3>Reason 1: Tech Readiness</h3>
      <p>Seattle's constant rain, steep hills, and frequent construction zones are perceptual challenges — but they're exactly the kind of challenges our Dataset B investment was designed to handle. Our balanced training data gives us defensible coverage across varied weather and road conditions, and our world model has already been stress-tested on compound scenarios like dense fog, dusk lighting, loose animals, and active construction simultaneously. Seattle doesn't require us to solve scenarios we haven't modeled; it requires us to deploy models we've already validated. Our reward function — calibrated at balanced assertiveness, with collision and close-call penalties weighted at 7 points each — fits Seattle's traffic culture well. The city rewards patient, deliberate driving over aggressive gap-taking, which is precisely the behavior our planner produces.</p>
      <h3>Reason 2: Data Moat Growth</h3>
      <p>Seattle grows a weather edge-case moat that no current Waymo city provides at scale. Phoenix gives us sun. San Francisco gives us fog. Seattle gives us sustained rain, hill-grade variance, and construction-heavy urban corridors — conditions that force our simulation library to expand in directions competitors haven't prioritized. With our $1B allocation weighted toward simulation (35%) and fleet expansion (30%), every Seattle mile generates targeted training signal that compounds into future model quality. The behavioral graph we build in Seattle — how the car handles a wet uphill merge, or a cyclist emerging from a construction detour — is data no rival can purchase.</p>
      <h3>Reason 3: Social License Path</h3>
      <p>Seattle has no prior Waymo incidents to overcome, which means we're writing the narrative from scratch. The social license risks are real — the Amalgamated Transit Union has a strong presence, and bike-access and disability advocates are organized and vocal — but none of these have escalated to the legislative blockades we're facing in New York or the active NHTSA investigation clouding Atlanta. Our preemptive plan: engage the ATU and major disability-access organizations in the first 60 days with a formal community advisory panel, not a press release. We commit to transparent incident reporting and a dedicated remote-operator hiring pipeline that draws from displaced transit workers. Waymo vehicles are roughly 3.5× safer than human drivers in injury-producing crashes — in a city that loses residents to traffic fatalities every year, that's a genuine offer, not a corporate talking point.</p>
      <h3>The Risk I'm Accepting</h3>
      <p>Seattle's weather complexity will surface perception edge cases we haven't fully solved — sustained heavy rain degrades sensor performance in ways our Phoenix and SF data don't fully capture. I'm accepting that our first operating months will include failure traces we'll need to label, retrain on, and redeploy from. This is manageable because our simulation pipeline was built for exactly this: encounter the scenario in the real world, generate 10,000 variations in simulation, close the gap before it becomes a public incident.</p>
      <h3>What I'd Watch in the First 6 Months</h3>
      <p>Three signals will tell me whether this was the right call: (1) average perception confidence scores in rain conditions — if they trend below our SF baseline, we accelerate the labeling budget; (2) ATU and city council sentiment, tracked monthly — early escalation toward legislation means we move the community advisory panel from advisory to decision-making; (3) rider rating distribution — if we're seeing Austin-style hesitation complaints in Seattle's hill intersections, the planner needs a reward function retune before it becomes a social media story.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="drafted-note">Drafted with Claude and edited for voice and accuracy.</p>
  </div>

