<!-- WHAT I LEARNED -->
<div class="learned">
  <div class="learned-inner">
    <h2>What I Learned</h2>
    <p class="learned-sub">Concepts I can now apply to any AI company, not just Waymo.</p>
    <div class="learned-grid">
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>The Long-Tail Problem</h4>
        <p>Common scenarios are easy to solve. Rare, compounding ones are where AI products fail — and they can't be solved with more of the same data.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>World Models &amp; Transfer Learning</h4>
        <p>AI systems can generate scenarios they've never recorded by composing ingredients they understand separately. That's the mechanism behind simulation as a moat.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>The Alignment Problem</h4>
        <p>An AI optimizes exactly what you tell it to — no more. The gap between what you asked for and what you actually wanted is where most AI deployments go wrong.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>The Prediction-Decision Gap</h4>
        <p>Predicting what's happening and deciding what to do about it are two different problems. Most AI failures live in the decision half, not the prediction half.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>Data Moats &amp; Compounding Advantage</h4>
        <p>The company with the best data pipeline usually wins — not because of better code, but because data that compounds on itself creates a lead that grows faster than competitors can close.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="learned-card">
        <h4>Social License</h4>
        <p>Technology working is necessary but not sufficient. A community has to want you there. Social license failures have killed more AI deployments than technical ones.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
